      "text": "\nSurely Protein Folding is an interesting problem, and great benefit will surely derive from solving it (to the extent that a \"solution\" is possible). Like sequencing the human genome, however, solving the protein folding problem will not \"unlock\" the secrets of life in any of our lifetimes. While crucial to the current paradigm for venture capital investment, unfettered hype about the \"promise\" of such \"solutions\" burdens the biopharm domain in the same way that similar hype burdened the AI community during the eighties. Those of us who are consumed by the mysteries these molecules present (including yours truly) need to constantly remind ourselves that we are laying the very bottom-most foundation stones of the building that will eventually arise. We are rather more like Lavoisier (who defined a \"chemical element\" and published the first table of them in 1789) and rather less like Thomas Edison or Henry Ford. I wrote the above paragraph to emphasize the \"ant-hill\", not to minimize the ants. -- [[Tom Stambaugh]].",
